See ruin hill Where smoke hanging still Like echo age long forgotten. There's story home Crushed beneath blackened stones And roof fell beams rotten. See, Saul Darby loved wife And laboured life To provide material possessions And built home Of finest wood stone And building soon became sole obsession. Oh took three hundred days For timber raised And silhouette seen miles around And gables reached high As eagles sky But took one night bring -- When Darby's castle tumbled ground. Though shared common bed There precious little said In moments set aside sleeping. For busy dreams filled With rooms he'd yet build And never heard young Helen Darby weeping. Then one night heard sound As laid pencil And traced door turned handle, And pale light moon, Through windows room, Split shadows two bodies lay entangled.
